{"id":"ev_da2bddc1f9744e37","runId":"run_251","type":"delegation","at":1782499418412,"data":{"workItemId":"wi_58899500ab6b48c5","atom":0,"task":"Add a daemon-up fail-fast guard to the runnerless `run-independent` CLI path (hardening item 2 of the runnerless priority).\n\nBACKGROUND: `cocoder run-independent <priorityId>` executes an `independent-of-runner` priority via the standalone daemon-free path (entrypoint `runStandalone`, invoking `runRun`). Today it bypasses `probeDaemon` entirely and never checks whether the daemon is actually live. If the daemon IS up, a non-destructive independent run will try to open the live store (`local/cocoder.db`) that the daemon owns and contend for the SQLite single-writer lock — with no clear, early message (cryptic lock error or hang). Scope item 3 already covered 'daemon down'; this closes 'daemon up, run anyway'.\n\nWHAT TO CHANGE:\n1. Locate the `run-independent` command entry and the `runStandalone` flow (search `runStandalone`, `run-independent`, `probeDaemon` across packages/core and packages/daemon/cli). Read how `probeDaemon` reports daemon liveness and how `runStandalone` resolves the store path before reusing it here.\n2. Before the standalone run opens/locks the store, probe whether the daemon is live. If a live daemon is detected, FAIL FAST with a clear, actionable error: explain that the daemon owns the live store and would contend for the single-writer lock, and tell the user to stop the daemon OR re-run with `--force`. Add a `--force` flag that downgrades the fail to a clearly-logged WARNING and proceeds. (For a `destructive` priority that already runs against an isolated scratch store, the live-store contention does not apply — if that distinction is cleanly available at this point, scope the guard to the live-store case; if not, keep the guard simple and uniform and note the limitation. Do not over-engineer.)\n3. Reuse the existing `probeDaemon` rather than writing a second daemon-liveness check.\n\nMUST NOT BREAK: the daemon-DOWN path (the normal runnerless flow proven in run_250) must behave exactly as before — no new prompt, no new failure when the daemon is absent. Do not couple the standalone path to the daemon beyond this read-only liveness probe.\n\nACCEPTANCE / EXIT CRITERION:\n- A test pins that when `probeDaemon` reports the daemon live, `run-independent` exits fast with a clear error mentioning the live store / single-writer lock and the remedy, and does NOT open the live store.\n- A test (or the existing run_250 no-daemon test) confirms the daemon-down path still completes unchanged, and that `--force` proceeds past the guard with a logged warning.\n- `pnpm typecheck` and the affected test suite pass. Report the exact test command and its output.\n\nWRITE SCOPE: the runnerless CLI/standalone path and its tests only. Do not touch the daemon runner, the commit spine, or unrelated store code."}}
